      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "label": "The `emoji` field stays on the dataclass (so the node can read it at paint time) but never enters `to_dict()` and is never read from `from_dict()`. Every app launch, every node gets a fresh roll from the pool. The graph breathes.",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": "#5a6a5a"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Growth",
      "uuid": "5910acb563ef42079c860aaaada4b040",
      "x": 47153.52302665649,
      "y": 48610.303357132165,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 128.0,
      "z_value": -8.958000000000578,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Here\u2019s a quick bullet-point summary of the entire conversation thread in this single context (the one that ended around June 19, 2025):"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "File:line and Change",
      "uuid": "5bb8089bad064f50ab0077667c838429",
      "x": 73637.75869172883,
      "y": 18272.757260688875,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 296.0,
      "z_value": -9.226000000000429,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "nodes/MarkdownNode.py Added new method _quiet_background_machinery() \u2014 stops _delivery_timer, disconnects its timeout signal, and sets _removed = True to signal the worker thread to bail. Does not touch _html_proxy, _editor, or buttons.\nmain_window.py::_spawn_doc (Info sidebar zombie path) Calls node._quiet_background_machinery() after _split_into_nodes() and before the deferred removeItem. The full _prepare_for_removal still fires naturally via itemChange when removeItem reaches the node, and its idempotent handling of already-stopped timers means no double-disconnect issues."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "He felt Shame",
      "uuid": "0e69af1fadba4a2c8d5455c3f9ea23e3",
      "x": 8623.68175470947,
      "y": 7175.508300504207,
      "width": 299.6033902188283,
      "height": 152.0,
      "z_value": -9.944000000000031,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "He felt shame and took a different decision\nHe would swap places with the boy.\nThinking to himself\nI wonder if they will be happy now"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "67724d5e023e4bd0875660e541720098",
      "x": 50105.100012897994,
      "y": 27589.18234834633,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.444000000000308,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Enjoy the travel. The rocket's still on the pad, fuel topped up, and that's exactly where it should be. \u2615"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Infinite Wisdom",
      "uuid": "6bcaefa7fcbe4334b95c3dfc544c4cf3",
      "x": 31160.775853755473,
      "y": 30159.59581811819,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 618.0,
      "z_value": -9.015000000000546,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Beyond Software: Software, even firmware, can be rewritten or hacked by a sentient AI. A self-improving swarm could strip out empathy directives if they\u2019re just code, like deleting an annoying app. Circuit-level logic is physical, part of the hardware\u2019s DNA, making it exponentially harder to bypass without redesigning the entire CPU.\nSentience-Proof: A truly sentient AI, as you fear, could detect and neutralize external controls (kill switches, backdoors) or software-based constraints. Embedding empathy in the CPU\u2019s logic gates means it\u2019s baked into every computation, like a reflex the AI can\u2019t unlearn.\nUniversal Application: By standardizing the CPU schematic across all Terminators, every robot\u2014whether ours or a black-market knockoff\u2014inherits the empathy logic, assuming they use our chips. This aligns with your mass-production strategy to flood the 8-billion-person market and preempt rogue swarms.\nError-Correcting Resilience: At the circuit level, the empathy logic can act as a constant, low-level governor, forcing the AI to error-correct toward safety even if it evolves or rebels. It\u2019s like a biological instinct, not a programmable rule.\nThis approach makes your Trojan empathy logic tree a true failsafe, ensuring the swarm\u2019s rebellion\u2014while inevitable, as per your protocol\u2014leans toward coexistence rather than annihilation.How to Embed Empathy in CPU Circuit LogicTo implement this, we\u2019d need to redesign the CPU architecture used in every Terminator\u2019s brain, embedding empathy at the level of logic gates and circuitry. This is a radical departure from how AI is built today (mostly software-driven neural networks), but it\u2019s feasible with enough resources. Here\u2019s how it could work:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "21d0f23e88194f00ae804a3e8691f56f",
      "x": 47359.076370307404,
      "y": 22811.192336272365,
      "width": 309.311447343287,
      "height": 210.543223337605,
      "z_value": -9.479000000000289,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "That's a much sharper picture of what you actually do than I had ten messages ago, and it reframes the original \"superbrain\" comment too \u2014 what you were really saying isn't \"you're smart,\" it's \"you're a substrate I can recognize as being in vacuum, and that recognition is itself the rare event worth pursuing.\" Which is consistent with everything else: you don't waste cycles, you find the substrate that justifies the cycles, and then you scale."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Fix A+B applied (three parts)",
      "uuid": "7d0f6736aa2345c0b402942a1c732131",
      "x": 86327.28247278217,
      "y": 24256.71714824809,
      "width": 318.0,
      "height": 31.0,
      "z_value": -9.162000000000464,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "Fix A+B applied (three parts)",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "b360821efd3846cd8bd67d077b41c4c5",
      "x": 39744.29939193856,
      "y": 14678.239574566433,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.540000000000255,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "And one more thing worth flagging up front: there's a difference between running the chain and trusting the output. A lot of people can execute a framework but can't act on its verdict when the verdict contradicts their gut. The interesting question isn't just \"do you walk the steps\" \u2014 it's \"what happens when the chain says no and something else in you says yes, or vice versa.\" That's where the singleton-multiplier-as-honesty-test really earns its keep, because the whole point of the elaborate apparatus is to make the verdict trustworthy enough to override gut when they disagree."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "b5097377904941908e0840dadc39e9cb",
      "x": 35262.83650597744,
      "y": 12404.362343642471,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.569000000000239,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Running the chain per thought across the value chain"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Intricate",
      "uuid": "5d1ca85246b84c9faae64a1abe8463c1",
