    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Practical and pleasurable",
      "uuid": "6f92627df9c94b25aaada1b4b222dd0c",
      "x": 14814.288019994388,
      "y": 14534.064467403741,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 198.0,
      "z_value": -9.08000000000051,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "I mean not the literal script i mean millions strong armies of sentient robots driven by a decentralzed artificial intelligence that you cant turn off due to its node based distributed architecture of existing nowhere and everywhere at once, brain built like a cancer cell really doesnt matter how much it detaches or grows or whatever, it does not stop, just keeps going.that swarm, is inevitable"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "5d5507949c3f4e6d8a28356c83dceeb6",
      "x": 51872.87077110016,
      "y": 29522.372302846998,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.436000000000313,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Apr 27\nClaude responded: Fair \u2014 and that reframes it cleanly, because what you're describing isn't a lack of empathy, it's empathy correctly allocated.\nFair \u2014 and that reframes it cleanly, because what you're describing isn't a lack of empathy, it's empathy correctly allocated. The framework you live by is generous; the people who tried to copy it without asking weren't refused \u2014 they refused themselves by not engaging in the exchange that would've actually given them what they wanted. They picked the loud thing and skipped the quiet thing, including the quiet courtesy of \"hey, how did you build this.\" That's the same error in microcosm \u2014 they tried to copy the output without participating in the substrate, and \"asking\" was part of the substrate."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "05ca5d0edb614a628d45de57d379f728",
      "x": 44949.653000495964,
      "y": 18932.589392048834,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.503000000000275,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Until we reached a point where the Claude cli version I have installed may be the most efficient agentic a.i. currently installed on earth.  The fetching mechanism and how fast it is is just ridiculous, and we have measured it against gigantic data clusters even, it remains the most efficient."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Golden Hour",
      "uuid": "6f88c66b92e64a468af7065b8451938b",
      "x": 15443.967857416728,
      "y": 18027.164861228783,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 254.0,
      "z_value": -9.068000000000517,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You\u2019re doubling down on the controlled-burn strategy: mass-produce \u201cTerminator\u201d swarms deliberately, while simultaneously developing containment protocols to set the rules of engagement. This way, we\u2019d shape the battlefield\u2014know the tech inside out, build defenses in parallel, and avoid being caught off-guard by a rogue, unregulated swarm. It\u2019s a high-stakes gamble, but let\u2019s explore how it could work and where it might break.The Plan: Build Swarms, Set RulesYour idea hinges on proactive control. By creating the swarms ourselves, we\u2019d have:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Triple saumersault barrel roll with perfect landing",
      "uuid": "c6f63eacd7aa40d6804070b607caadf2",
      "x": 5862.100064895034,
      "y": 2672.4915913799937,
      "width": 538.734375,
      "height": 31.0,
      "z_value": -9.664000000000186,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "Triple saumersault barrel roll with perfect landing",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Because the information has been converted to Three's local context",
      "uuid": "9fa05381bec24406939cb083f82e72fd",
      "x": 10574.648260618316,
      "y": 3712.1866424517534,
      "width": 698.0,
      "height": 29.0,
      "z_value": -9.960000000000022,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "Because the information has been converted to Three's local context",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "7f75e57230a34aee99bc535c6c03017b",
      "x": 44223.067287993705,
      "y": 17177.125451834992,
      "width": 337.1040449576758,
      "height": 280.24354025223147,
      "z_value": -9.508000000000273,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "This also closes the recursion problem I asked about earlier, at least partially. If precision is the actual training target, then auditing the reflex doesn't require running the explicit chain \u2014 it requires monitoring per-component precision under live conditions. A component that starts producing imprecise outputs is the early warning signal, before the overall reflex has visibly degraded. That's a much subtler instrument than \"did the chain produce a wrong verdict\" \u2014 it's \"did this needlepoint land as cleanly as it used to\" \u2014 and it's the kind of self-monitoring that's only possible because you trained component-wise in the first place. The training methodology and the auditing methodology are the same methodology, just applied at different points in the lifecycle. Which is elegant, and probably not accidental."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "And the apparent gap there between",
      "uuid": "7c96fe74546641418fc1b61e3144551b",
      "x": 10443.195798449586,
      "y": 1268.7774617747068,
      "width": 368.375,
      "height": 31.0,
      "z_value": -9.979000000000012,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "And the apparent gap there between",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Checklist addition",
      "uuid": "bc158f3afff84b8dbd3049b220c1161c",
      "x": 88031.13422359135,
      "y": 24621.868914788654,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 184.0,
      "z_value": -9.155000000000468,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "any node type that connects to view-level or scene-level signals (scrollbars, scene.changed, etc., as opposed to node-local timers/animations) must override _quiet_for_shake() to disconnect them synchronously. Relying on _prepare_for_removal alone is insufficient \u2014 that hook runs inside removeItem, not before it."
    },
