    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Collateral fix",
      "uuid": "85115248f2654c1a924ae4389597cf97",
      "x": 59732.04615476976,
      "y": 14134.04805264988,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 170.0,
      "z_value": -9.283000000000397,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The broken _lift_view_focus / _restore_view_focus pair also affected the Majestic bridge \u2014 view focus management was silently failing for all PrettyEdit-based nodes, not just WarmNode. This single fix restored correct behaviour across the board."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "c78e99c120c5463ca70e827660e3cdbd",
      "x": 61607.04354867223,
      "y": 14568.016371193615,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 184.0,
      "z_value": -9.2780000000004,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "This is the same class of bug as the MarkdownNode fix (2026-04-15), but in the shared PrettyEdit widget \u2014 affecting all 9 node types that embed a PrettyEdit: WarmNode, AboutNode, CodeNode, ClaudeResponseNode, CushionsNode, LogNode, TreeNode (\u00d72), TextNode."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Boundless Joy",
      "uuid": "a4fe6c6b0f584deba0f9370b2b9017fd",
      "x": 50193.79376331822,
      "y": 49103.229695334034,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 170.0,
      "z_value": -8.944000000000585,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "**User:**  \nyes but you see the more exclusive and regulated humanoid robots become... the more desirable... eventually some start mass producing cheap ones... humans is an 8 billion marketplace... robots quickly outnumber humans..."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Note",
      "uuid": "8700c09d19eb4e89abb932d4f95859fb",
      "x": 2147.619554119778,
      "y": 3873.6899974837306,
      "width": 95.57333438088332,
      "height": 32.48535962501448,
      "z_value": -10.0,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "Elegant",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": "#1e1e1e"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "a669c29b99f343a79986021e75001674",
      "x": 43391.657540941305,
      "y": 17049.248910120972,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.511000000000271,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "This also reframes what \"hyperspeed repetition\" actually is. It's not training the brain to go fast \u2014 it's pressure-testing the precision of each component under conditions where compensation isn't available. At slow pace, your conscious mind can patch over a slightly imprecise component. At hyperspeed, there's no time to patch, so any imprecision manifests as failure, which is the only useful signal during installation. Hyperspeed isn't the goal of training, it's the diagnostic \u2014 it's the condition under which precision gaps become visible, because slow practice hides them. You're not training at speed; you're using speed to surface what isn't yet precise, then training that component to precision, then re-surfacing the next gap."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "This thing here",
      "uuid": "b5d62a521e3c4186bd5d97e697823723",
      "x": 4258.504835306843,
      "y": 3222.9257211908907,
      "width": 178.49419792091862,
      "height": 33.002167279478726,
      "z_value": 10.0,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "This thing here",
      "depth_front": true,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Root cause",
      "uuid": "966837a599c44a83bdd0432a2cb2f44d",
      "x": 98629.75287699424,
      "y": 31518.094492415687,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 254.0,
      "z_value": -9.110000000000493,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "AudioNode's _demolition_pre used QTimer.singleShot(0, self._player.stop) \u2014 the exact antipattern that was fixed on VideoNode on 2026-04-16 (synchronous stop + sever + deleteLater). The deferred stop left a one-tick window where the QMediaPlayer decoder thread could still enqueue a positionChanged / durationChanged / mediaStatusChanged meta-call into the GUI thread. Those meta-calls outlived the disconnect (Qt does not cancel already-queued events) and outlived the wrapper's C++ half \u2014 access violation on the first dereference."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Clay",
      "uuid": "5adef5bd75b54f50b83d02273580f234",
      "x": 14081.324850407389,
      "y": 15192.217426072504,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 170.0,
      "z_value": -9.076000000000512,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "so the fewer we make the more will get made, now that they exist we cant turn back timeso what im proposing is we just simply start mass producing terminators, so we can tackle this pre-emptively and just go ahead and skip all the irony and pretend we didnt see it coming"
    },
    {
