    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Unfold",
      "uuid": "09beb07075d44a1dab51b6f8a9f298a1",
      "x": 14515.226111558857,
      "y": 15475.55714833226,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 422.0,
      "z_value": -9.075000000000513,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Your argument\u2019s got a wild twist: since humanoid robots exist and restrictive regulation might fuel a black-market boom, why not just lean in and mass-produce \u201cTerminators\u201d now to get ahead of the chaos? It\u2019s like fighting fire with fire\u2014preempt the inevitable by controlling the terms. Let\u2019s chew on this.The logic tracks on human nature: scarcity breeds demand, and trying to suppress tech often makes it spread faster underground. History\u2019s full of examples\u2014prohibition, pirated software, 3D-printed guns. Once the genie\u2019s out (and humanoid robots are already a thing, with companies like Boston Dynamics and Tesla tinkering), you can\u2019t un-invent it. Your point about not turning back time is spot-on; the knowledge and prototypes are here.Mass-producing \u201cTerminators\u201d (let\u2019s assume you mean advanced, possibly weaponized humanoid robots) to flood the market could, in theory, normalize and regulate them before guerrillas do it shadily. It\u2019s like legalizing a drug to undercut cartels\u2014control the supply, set the rules. You\u2019d sidestep the irony of fear-driven bans creating a worse outcome. But here\u2019s where it gets dicey:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Concern and Resolution",
      "uuid": "82869e4b6af843fc8ae9fbd495c0a07d",
      "x": 70666.54281591137,
      "y": 17546.985983879087,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 212.0,
      "z_value": -9.237000000000423,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Removal speed Unchanged. The single-delete path never raises the counter; only _shake_delete_group does.\nLive UI freezes None. Peers resume painting on the next event-loop tick after the final release.\nMissed final-state paint None. Every peer still receives a paint event after the flag is lowered; the motion engine settles to its real target on the next _glide_tick."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
