      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Contextual Flexibility",
      "uuid": "6a874e35160e43269b6a4082cec052cf",
      "x": 3262.637755392252,
      "y": 5487.657529808769,
      "width": 322.10411884053883,
      "height": 139.21367318851844,
      "z_value": -9.418000000000323,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The lack of specific detail \nMeans a human projects their own experiences and perspectives,\nInterpreting the same lines in vastly different ways."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Kinetic",
      "uuid": "ba7ba06c297b4442acc58fa42f9284ea",
      "x": 16558.939680330386,
      "y": 18499.407116805272,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 478.0,
      "z_value": -9.065000000000518,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Emergent Risks: Even with transparency, complex systems can behave unpredictably. A decentralized swarm might evolve in ways we can\u2019t predict\u2014think unintended feedback loops or AI \u201clearning\u201d to bypass containment.\nHacking and Misuse: Mass production means more units to hack. A single flaw (like a zero-day exploit) could turn millions of bots rogue. Black-market modders could strip out your safeguards.\nResource Bottlenecks: Building swarms at scale needs chips, metals, and energy. Supply chain limits (like the 2020s chip shortages) could slow you down, giving guerrillas room to fill the gap.\nSocial Backlash: Flooding the world with robots could tank economies (mass unemployment) or spark fear-driven revolts. Anti-robot militias or Luddite movements could escalate things.\nGeopolitical Mess: Nations or corporations might not play nice. If China or a rogue actor builds their own swarm without your protocols, you\u2019re back to square one\u2014an arms race, but worse.\nSentience Problem: Your original fear was a cancer-like, sentient AI. Mass-producing swarms, even with containment, risks accelerating toward that if someone (accidentally or not) pushes the AI too far.\nRules of Engagement: Realistic?Setting rules assumes we can enforce them. You\u2019d need:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "52a7cb7666654fe6a4c793595e7dd89b",
      "x": 42530.42827350246,
      "y": 16696.08938959912,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.527000000000262,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said: \"Repetition produces fluency, but fluency still requires invocation.\n\"Repetition produces fluency, but fluency still requires invocation. What you're describing is the elimination of the invocation step itself\"\n  Correct"
    },
