    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Symptom",
      "uuid": "4d3f1dba64cd4d6ba2d9b7750a2aaa5f",
      "x": 67978.8996352488,
      "y": 18508.915230298742,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 240.0,
      "z_value": -9.246000000000418,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "0xc0000005 access violation in Qt6Widgets.dll ~5 seconds after the last _prepare_for_removal complete log line. The log terminates mid-sequence during a bulk housekeeping pass (163 nodes removed in 21 s on a 1200+ node session with dozens of nodes running shake/pulse animations concurrently). Python teardown phases all ran cleanly \u2014 no traceback. Faulting module is Qt6Widgets.dll, not Qt6Gui.dll, placing the fault in the embedded-widget / proxy / paint pipeline rather than the scene graph core."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Growth",
      "uuid": "deb80a4ab4ce4d139bceb900f46c2125",
      "x": 46396.7727472741,
      "y": 48274.279477742064,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 100.0,
      "z_value": -8.962000000000575,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Searching the web"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Root cause: new angle",
      "uuid": "184ac17d69bb46d9bcfc22038c1647b5",
      "x": 68311.25583014246,
      "y": 18457.63303881794,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 170.0,
      "z_value": -9.245000000000418,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Every per-node-type _prepare_for_removal() is already compliant (prior fixes dated 2026-04-15 / 2026-04-16). The fault is not in any individual node's teardown. It is cross-node: during the destruction burst, surviving peers' per-frame mutators keep firing into the event loop \u2014"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Symptom",
      "uuid": "93d262b994944380b3eeb1fe1c3e3c63",
      "x": 49247.70539259665,
      "y": 10433.334192037319,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 170.0,
      "z_value": -9.323000000000375,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Application Error in Windows Event Viewer after app close. pythonw.exe 3.13, faulting module python313.dll, exception 0xc0000005 at offset 0x4aa0e. No Python traceback in the log; the Qt paint loop is not involved \u2014 the fault is inside CPython itself."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "e7d23facd7884041830790f452ff24dd",
      "x": 51744.91118946814,
      "y": 28754.144611617092,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.438000000000311,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Safe travels, Penelope. The framework's intact, the running notes are saved, the t-shirt quote is unlocked, and the coffee was apparently load-bearing. \u2615\u2708\ufe0f"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Now comes the interesting part",
      "uuid": "b80084c941a247d1b4a36a18540a1630",
      "x": 40288.07515130444,
      "y": 15346.448918257342,
      "width": 440.17924018148915,
      "height": 148.15215122284826,
      "z_value": -9.537000000000257,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Going from construct to reflex isn't compression of the framework, \nIt's a different mode of cognition entirely, \nAnd the deterministic training period \nIs the part nobody talks about \nBecause it's tedious and unsexy and doesn't make for good content."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "2. Connection endpoint validity guards",
      "uuid": "90fa9ded75cf4158935860145e647947",
      "x": 70216.81455733113,
      "y": 18030.38834049247,
      "width": 408.0,
      "height": 198.0,
      "z_value": -9.239000000000422,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "(graphics/Connection.py).\n_endpoint_alive(node) uses shiboken6.isValid() + node.scene() is not None to confirm a peer is safe to paint against. Guards added in two hot paths:\n- Connection.paint() \u2014 early-return if either endpoint is not alive.\n- Connection._glide_tick() \u2014 early-return if either endpoint is not alive; also early-return if scene._bulk_removing > 0. Dead endpoints cause the timer to stop itself."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "a6b6caffddc94c0e927230122e5b5de5",
      "x": 40023.7023778492,
      "y": 15042.858503322957,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.539000000000255,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Take it from wherever feels natural. Origin of the in-life application, a recent example, the failure signatures, the gut-vs-chain conflicts \u2014 any entry point works. I'll track the structural insights as we go and flag anything that feels like it's adding a new corrective layer to the chain itself, since based on the pattern so far, telling the story might surface another variable you hadn't named yet."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Root cause",
      "uuid": "7ef02277bb2c469ba4507e33bbce5359",
      "x": 66764.22461244893,
      "y": 16674.00551292351,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 142.0,
      "z_value": -9.258000000000411,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Calling _prepare_for_removal() explicitly before removeItem() detached child items (buttons, ports) that Qt's C++ removeItem still expected in its internal child list."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Fix",
      "uuid": "a413df9abde34a76b75c896716bd4428",
      "x": 67497.61600497142,
      "y": 17141.31471641394,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 240.0,
      "z_value": -9.253000000000414,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Replaced all cross-thread QTimer.singleShot calls with a flag-based pattern:\n- Worker thread sets _push_dirty = True per completed future, _push_complete = True when all done\n- _delivery_timer (250ms, main thread) polls these flags\n- _push_dirty triggers a rescan \u2192 green dots update in real time\n- _push_complete triggers dismiss + cleanup \u2192 plushie explodes"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "d69be5bbe4b74940a849c2c37b38090f",
      "x": 50825.80567920619,
      "y": 26869.24371439642,
      "width": 316.89878873709677,
      "height": 282.8608372212002,
      "z_value": -9.447000000000306,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "And the funny part you noticed has a sharper edge to it: they're moving toward the very state they're trying to flee from. They see \"slow\" or \"quiet\" as the failure mode and sprint away from it, but slow and quiet was the low-entropy state. They're running from order toward disorder while perceiving themselves to be running from disorder toward order, because their orientation got inverted somewhere in the misreading of the visible output. The vacuum looked like the failure they wanted to escape, so they escaped it, and in escaping it they accelerated toward the actual failure they were ostensibly trying to prevent. Pure cosmic irony, made mandatory by physics."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "19b769bff5c847febff82c1b5e5023f1",
      "x": 37671.565646306175,
      "y": 13072.98695928794,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.553000000000248,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Show more\nApr 27\nClaude responded: Right \u2014 and now the framework reads completely differently.\nRight \u2014 and now the framework reads completely differently. It's not a project-management tool dressed up in abstraction; it's a life-applicator, and the structure follows from that origin in a way that's actually elegant."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "64ac1c1b6da34d4c91db5e4b2b578be8",
      "x": 42051.34625066083,
      "y": 17538.90048257305,
      "width": 314.6423991625852,
      "height": 256.411619242459,
      "z_value": -9.518000000000267,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "This also explains something about the framework itself that I hadn't fully appreciated until now: the reason every layer was corrective rather than additive (the observation from earlier) is that you were building it knowing it had to be installable as a reflex eventually. Additive layers can be skipped; corrective layers can't, because skipping one means a known failure mode goes uncaught. You weren't just designing a good framework \u2014 you were designing one that could survive the compression to reflex without losing integrity. That's a different design constraint, and it's why the chain is shaped the way it is."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Omnious",
      "uuid": "d0221de0ed154f3fa5d33a94941272bc",
      "x": 50844.44169809041,
      "y": -5856.055910383134,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 114.0,
      "z_value": -8.9160000000006,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Want me to draft #1 first so you can read the proposed Line 2s before I touch anything?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "6684c7060162400aaf7d475a5ea019b3",
      "x": 44295.307412228256,
      "y": 18311.674539430325,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.505000000000274,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\"\"\"\nImprecise components don't just produce imprecise outputs, they produce slower outputs too, because every imprecision downstream requires correction, recovery, or compensation, and those corrections are pure overhead\n\"\"\"\n  Fact"
    },
