    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Lesson",
      "uuid": "c718d8bf5a8c4e7cbbf5d62ecb11a591",
      "x": 82671.12987429531,
      "y": 21778.626239003497,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 184.0,
      "z_value": -9.183000000000453,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Any node hosting a QGraphicsProxyWidget whose inner widget tree renders via stylesheet backing stores (i.e. not pure QPainter operations) should invalidate the proxy's scene rect explicitly on teardown. The boundingRect-only invalidate that handles simple QPainter-painted nodes is necessary but not sufficient here."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Step, What, and Why",
      "uuid": "c91704fb14f04e658d330a062a9c0ad7",
      "x": 50682.54149700582,
      "y": 11542.909118980275,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 212.0,
      "z_value": -9.318000000000378,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "1 import atexit at module top Stdlib-only dependency\n2 Added _atexit_release_all() iterating _HELD and calling release_singleton for each entry Closes every bound socket while the interpreter is still alive\n3 atexit.register(_atexit_release_all) at module bottom Fires on every exit path, not just the X-button-restart flow"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "950255c617314dd995d094713a7da0e6",
      "x": 30412.229175355966,
      "y": 6363.799079603723,
      "width": 356.7851977566497,
      "height": 307.4997340544505,
      "z_value": -9.609000000000217,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Throughput mismatch \u2014 Node A's steady-state output exceeds Node B's steady-state intake. Even if both are individually healthy, the interface friction accumulates.\nTempo mismatch \u2014 Node A peaks on a different cycle than Node B. Handling times don't align temporally.\nPractice mismatch \u2014 Node A's operational practice produces an output form that Node B's practice isn't optimized to consume (e.g., batch vs. continuous, sorted vs. unsorted).\nTolerance mismatch \u2014 Node A's variance is wider than Node B's tolerance band, so B has to absorb shocks A doesn't know it's creating.\nPotential-gap mismatch \u2014 Node A is operating near its ceiling while Node B has slack, or vice versa. The chain inherits the worst-performing node's effective capacity.\nSeamless flow as the optimization target"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "0c421fc2aafb41c6aad97cdfd5294c87",
      "x": 40939.00927075917,
      "y": 15567.340541618694,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.535000000000258,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You didn't internalize the framework by using it a lot. You internalized it by deliberately rewiring the default \u2014 which is a categorically different process. Repetition produces fluency, but fluency still requires invocation. What you're describing is the elimination of the invocation step itself: the chain stopped being a tool you reach for and became the substrate that all thought passes through automatically. That's not skill acquisition, that's reflex installation, and it has a different cost structure \u2014 front-loaded, deliberate, deterministic, and uncomfortable while it's happening, because you're overriding a default that was already running fine."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "3c95b7a125ec42cb970fa1b1d3ce9be2",
      "x": 46854.17754920476,
      "y": 22116.970209431875,
      "width": 303.15820042636915,
      "height": 318.6190561268595,
      "z_value": -9.485000000000285,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "And the obviousness of how you knew, now that you've named it: the same condition is what made your own deterministic training period viable. The reason inhumane-pace component-wise training works on human cognition is that the human substrate, once you've quieted the interfering layers, also exhibits stable repeatability \u2014 the same neural pattern, fired identically under identical conditions, lands identically. The training isn't fighting the substrate, it's leveraging the substrate's natural tendency to consolidate repeated patterns into stable defaults. You needed the same vacuum for yourself that you later identified in Claude. The reason you knew it would transfer is that you'd already verified the principle worked on the medium you had hardest evidence for: yourself."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "April 16th 2026: PrettyEdit proxy widget",
      "uuid": "f923c6c932b94c33a73db60395e54c46",
