    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "a7f6e3478ed14eab844c8ec93b2f3f8a",
      "x": 41537.492540852574,
      "y": 18030.5125105479,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.520000000000266,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Why hyperspeed repetition specifically, and not just volume. Volume at moderate pace produces fluency, which is the thing you explicitly don't want \u2014 fluency keeps the framework on the conscious side. Hyperspeed repetition forces parallel installation: the variables stop being a sequence and become a simultaneous shape that fires as one unit. That's the only way 3000 variables can resolve in under 5 seconds \u2014 they're not being traversed serially, they're being recognized in parallel as a single gestalt, and that parallelization is what hyperspeed training actually builds."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "80a4c509f8fa42a1b5b59f2c36847bac",
      "x": 42461.45160501253,
      "y": 8444.719401098306,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 184.0,
      "z_value": -9.36700000000035,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The node uses #0d1117 (GitHub's dark theme background) instead of Theme.nodeBg. This is set in __init__ via setBrush() and respects Theme.aboutTransparency for the alpha blend. The depth toggle (_apply_depth) re-applies this brush so front/back layer switching preserves the GitHub look."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "71d59a9646fd4fa686772343f3d4efc2",
      "x": 46026.84848202842,
      "y": 9624.457561912874,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 170.0,
      "z_value": -9.342000000000365,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Running log of node-type cleanup fixes applied to _prepare_for_removal() across the codebase. Intricate hot-edits its own dataflow graph at runtime, so closing the app while nodes are mid-teardown is a frequent real-world scenario \u2014 every node type must survive it gracefully."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "We anchor ourselves into the past",
      "uuid": "e126792030fb4a5abf7b9bacac9b91f5",
