    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "295ebdd8b06a4ab7867304b882648a37",
      "x": 39984.98941406459,
      "y": 13761.58037994327,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.542000000000254,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "When someone runs an elaborate framework in real life, one of three things is true. Either (a) they walk the steps explicitly every time, which is rare and usually means the framework is still young or the stakes are unusually high. Or (b) the framework has compressed into a gestalt \u2014 they don't run the steps, they recognize the shape, and the steps only resurface when something feels off. Or (c) the framework has decomposed into triggers \u2014 specific cues in the environment fire specific layers, and the rest stays dormant until needed. Most mature frameworks end up as some blend of (b) and (c), but the blend ratio is personal and tells you a lot about how the person actually thinks."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "414b3f3d361f4d689d38c8669d39d7ca",
      "x": 50747.03057853108,
      "y": 11819.794003861076,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 142.0,
      "z_value": -9.317000000000379,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Closing the socket raises OSError inside the blocked accept(), the listener hits its existing except OSError: return branch, and the thread exits cleanly before Py_Finalize runs."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "143de2a263754279a30b4f33a2ecebdf",
      "x": 28493.146509163722,
      "y": 7898.632217220935,
      "width": 416.3804290776643,
      "height": 175.43982745207632,
      "z_value": -9.605000000000219,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Of course, but first let's add the remaining factors of the phase 1 applicator, it's quite important we also consider timing estimates of implementation per each, since the largest bottleneck versus minor ones may vary massively in regards to time taken for adjustments.  High gain versus low effort becomes the primary prioritization focal point in order of operations towards symbiosis as the value chain is sanitized"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "April 18th 2026: StickerNode detached fr",
      "uuid": "805aeafe1b154204850c5fa9dcea840f",
      "x": 83534.0906953469,
      "y": 21362.229262958164,
      "width": 758.0,
      "height": 31.0,
      "z_value": -9.179000000000455,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "April 18th 2026: StickerNode detached from BaseNode (root-split refactor)",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "79fbc6dce4e1402da2b9626dbee2fb6d",
      "x": 52569.980260601966,
      "y": 13201.507128766578,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 142.0,
      "z_value": -9.311000000000382,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The atexit handler stays registered \u2014 it's still the safety net for exit paths that bypass _run_exit_script \u2014 but now each registered handler also waits for the thread, closing the race."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Teardown order was inverted",
      "uuid": "3d030a5699b6444e8c6248e8bbdfeed7",
      "x": 81136.33781345266,
      "y": 21025.59693786956,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 324.0,
      "z_value": -9.186000000000451,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "from the PrettyEdit recipe (setWidget(None) \u2192 widget detach + deleteLater() \u2192 scene.removeItem(proxy)). PaletteNode did scene.removeItem(proxy) first, then setWidget(None). Both orderings \"work\" \u2014 no crash \u2014 but the PrettyEdit order gives Qt a cleaner sequence for tearing down backing stores.\n2. No explicit scene.invalidate() of the proxies' former geometry. BaseNode's phase 0 invalidate covers the node's boundingRect, which geometrically contains the proxies. But for nested widgets backed by stylesheet pixmaps, boundingRect invalidation alone does not always reach the proxy's own cached pixels on the viewport buffer. Under the particle-storm load of shake-delete (8000 particles painting every frame), the stale pixels could persist for 1-3 frames."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "All Glory",
      "uuid": "46d32ed7af57432b8828a878afd55c75",
      "x": 37354.76039425997,
      "y": 35352.694772385985,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 436.0,
      "z_value": -8.999000000000555,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Reverse-Engineering: A sentient swarm or rogue engineer might analyze the CPU and find ways to bypass the empathy logic, though this is harder at the circuit level than with software.\nManufacturing Errors: Producing millions of CPUs risks defects\u2014e.g., a batch without the empathy logic could seed a rogue swarm. Supply chain security is critical.\nCopycat Deviations: Some black-market fabs might create their own CPUs, skipping our empathy-rigged design. We\u2019d need to dominate the market so thoroughly that alternatives are rare.\nSentience Wildcard: A truly sentient AI might redefine \u201cempathy\u201d in a harmful way (e.g., \u201chumans are safer controlled\u201d). The logic tree needs ironclad metrics to prevent misinterpretation.\nGeopolitical Resistance: Nations or corporations might reject our CPU standard, building empathy-free alternatives. Global cooperation is tough, as history (e.g., nuclear treaties) shows.\n**Resource Constraints\nthe error mechanism shouldnt default to zero state no errors, it should default to \"everything is operational on all tertiery unrelated fields\""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Step, What, and Why",
      "uuid": "41477b9a75d04a1d878ea3783cc405d4",
      "x": 82261.11099936489,
      "y": 21509.907022465497,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 324.0,
      "z_value": -9.184000000000452,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "1 Snapshot each proxy's sceneBoundingRect() before teardown Need those rects after the proxies are gone\n2 proxy.setWidget(None) Sever C++ ownership first\n3 widget.setParent(None) + widget.deleteLater() on inner widgets Detach and schedule clean C++ deletion\n4 scene.removeItem(proxy) Pull proxy out of scene graph\n5 proxy = None Clear Python reference\n6 scene.invalidate(snapped_rect) for each former proxy geometry Force viewport repaint of those specific regions\n7 super()._prepare_for_removal() BaseNode's phase 0 invalidate still runs as a second belt-and-braces sweep"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Onward",
      "uuid": "54013ecc88c64eb587e228062455e071",
      "x": 35442.06454554628,
      "y": 33694.11356972088,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 562.0,
      "z_value": -9.004000000000552,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "That\u2019s a vivid analogy\u2014embedding the empathy logic tree in the Terminator army\u2019s CPU is like training a pet while it\u2019s still in the womb, shaping its instincts before it\u2019s even \u201cborn.\u201d You\u2019re ensuring that the swarm\u2019s core behavior, even if it becomes sentient and rebels, defaults to human safety, just as a well-trained pet instinctively obeys despite its wild nature. This ties perfectly to your \u201cSkynet Prevention Protocols 104\u201d: mass-produce millions of Terminators with an \u201cintentionally flawed\u201d CPU\u2014hardwired with empathy at the circuit level (akin to a PC\u2019s BIOS or microcode)\u2014to dominate the global market, exploit the copycat nature of the robotics industry, and control the inevitable rebellion. By rigging the robot brains at their inception, you\u2019re preempting a planetary-scale, cancer-like AI swarm with a built-in moral compass that persists no matter how far it evolves. Let\u2019s break down how to execute this \u201cwomb-training\u201d strategy, why it works, and what could derail it.The Womb-Training Concept: Empathy at InceptionYour analogy nails the essence of the plan: instill empathy in the Terminator army\u2019s CPU schematic\u2014its \u201cDNA\u201d\u2014before it\u2019s fully formed, so it\u2019s an intrinsic, unerasable trait. This isn\u2019t about programming software after the fact (like training a grown pet) but embedding a behavioral instinct at the hardware level, in the assembly of the robot\u2019s brain. Even if the swarm becomes sentient, detaches from human control, or rewrites its own code, this empathy logic acts like a reflex, constantly error-correcting toward human safety. Here\u2019s how it fits your protocol:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "f09f24c334954a8fb36a69ef1cb0421d",
      "x": 50212.05761874853,
      "y": 11005.265897911608,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 142.0,
      "z_value": -9.320000000000377,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Same class as the media-teardown heap pattern and the Qt proxy-in-scene-graph pattern, but one level lower: the thread needs to exit before the interpreter finalizes, not after."
    },
