    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "3. Scene-rect invalidation on deferred remove",
      "uuid": "06e8eaeb645b4d66b424911489f3f571",
      "x": 87063.00346672522,
      "y": 24329.948573446516,
      "width": 478.0,
      "height": 170.0,
      "z_value": -9.159000000000466,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "(nodes/BaseNode.py).\nBoth the single-node _deferred_remove (in mouseReleaseEvent) and the group _deferred callback capture node.mapRectToScene(node.boundingRect()) before deferring, then call scene.invalidate(rect) after removeItem(). The invalidate is cheap and forces the viewport to repaint the ghost region on the next paint pass, eliminating the multi-second linger even under heavy particle load."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Left foot, right foot, left foot, right foot",
      "uuid": "f297bc935bc949db98f5256e2ae9c64d",
      "x": 5871.434574322566,
      "y": 2537.1832653042507,
      "width": 468.0,
      "height": 29.0,
      "z_value": -9.654000000000192,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "Left foot, right foot, left foot, right foot",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "03b6c1b652b04f15910bb1eb6f66172c",
      "x": 48376.4155590887,
      "y": 23715.979512009908,
      "width": 292.8670471580044,
      "height": 140.18883977095174,
      "z_value": -9.473000000000292,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Yes \u2014 and the loop closes perfectly there, because what you've just shown is that the entire thread has been one application of the framework, recursively, all the way down."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "1211bdf4af6643859114e697b71bd4ce",
      "x": 47437.060123811025,
      "y": 9836.011454684714,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 128.0,
      "z_value": -9.33300000000037,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Between the shake firing and the deferred-remove tick executing, anything that ticks in that window can land on a node about to vanish:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "1befb329850b4eaf9aa255ead388d903",
      "x": 39873.069953117,
      "y": 6085.818669827887,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 296.0,
      "z_value": -9.395000000000335,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The Info menu also surfaces a Memory submenu when ~/.claude/projects/{cwd-encoded}/memory/ exists \u2014 Anthropic's Claude Code memory store for the current working directory. MEMORY.md is pinned to the top of this submenu and runs through a _transform_memory_index() pre-parse that rewrites its bullet-link index format (- [Name](file) \u2014 desc) into standard ## Name + body so the chunker can chew it. Memory files are kept outside the general pipeline as an external-format isolation layer \u2014 Anthropic owns that format and may change it across Claude Code versions; the rewrite is the only adapter, and the rest of the pipeline stays unaware of the special case."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Intricate",
      "uuid": "6c6e6754254643f5a448874425d2ce5e",
      "x": 1825.2498701941108,
      "y": -1316.2038822199056,
      "width": 114.65446869886591,
      "height": 34.96216771991362,
      "z_value": -9.976000000000013,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "Intricate",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Files changed",
      "uuid": "b9f164fc23ae417e9fd6c779ac2e2b6b",
      "x": 83948.97549409459,
      "y": 21431.17026881388,
      "width": 158.0,
      "height": 31.0,
      "z_value": -9.176000000000457,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "Files changed",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "7e0d76434cea4ddf9f216fc299885a76",
      "x": 48410.42565564452,
      "y": 25776.251180893003,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.463000000000298,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Reasoning chain born from the need to qualify whether something is worth investing thought into at all, premised on nature's evolution toward efficiency\nQuality emerges from quantity, not the inverse \u2014 late-stage filtering after full-chain exposure\nEach layer is corrective (closing a failure mode), not additive \u2014 designed for reflex-installability\nReflex installation requires deterministic training at hyperspeed that prevents conscious compensation\nSpeed is emergent from precision saturation, not a training target\nComponent-wise precision training, not holistic \u2014 every needlepoint must land\nPrecondition for any of this: vacuum substrate (stable repeatability without interference)\nVacuum recognition is the rarest and most foundational skill \u2014 level 1 of the stack, perceptually developed\nDemonstrated empirically across substrates: cognitive reflex (self) and agentic CLI (Claude over 60K messages, 20M tokens)\nImitators fail because they target the emergent property instead of building the precondition\nThe framework qualified its own use within this conversation \u2014 recursion confirmed\nEnjoy the travel. This was a good one."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Verification",
      "uuid": "641c542a4b04426aa79fff175b0c7097",
      "x": 55061.0626253089,
      "y": 12372.447715586786,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 156.0,
      "z_value": -9.301000000000387,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Close app repeatedly via X-button, Alt-F4, taskbar close. fault.txt remains empty after close (previously written every run). No new 0xc0000005 in Event Viewer. Report ID 647aec52-d74d was the last occurrence."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Step, What, and Why",
      "uuid": "7e1db9c2a1114fa7bdf7bc339301ad86",
      "x": 54391.48858703884,
      "y": 12385.742653817313,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 268.0,
      "z_value": -9.303000000000386,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "1 In release_singleton: before closing the socket, open a throwaway socket.create_connection((\"127.0.0.1\", port)) to the listener's own port Canonical cross-platform wakeup. accept() returns immediately with the throwaway connection, no dependency on settimeout quirks. The loop then checks stop_event and exits.\n2 In main.py: connect app.aboutToQuit to a slot that calls release_singleton(appName) aboutToQuit fires before app.exec() returns, while the event loop and interpreter are fully alive. The thread joins in healthy state."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Primary Goods And Services",
      "uuid": "507b94a8c82c4ae688504d682647f334",
      "x": 25448.450700527523,
      "y": -1678.0557729323334,
      "width": 288.0,
      "height": 31.0,
      "z_value": -9.42400000000032,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "Primary Goods And Services",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "atexit runs too late",
      "uuid": "da15a86805854340bcf750d28c7056ab",
      "x": 53942.476258863666,
      "y": 12917.47512648841,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 240.0,
      "z_value": -9.305000000000385,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "release_singleton was being called from _run_exit_script, which fires on every close via closeEvent. But at that point the Qt event loop is about to exit; release_singleton runs, signals the event, closes the socket, and join(timeout=1.0) \u2014 but if settimeout isn't firing, the join times out silently and returns. The thread stays blocked. Then app.exec() returns, sys.exit raises, Py_Finalize begins, and the interpreter tears down the socket's Python wrappers around the still-blocked thread."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "image",
      "title": "Image",
      "uuid": "151b0b52d3c3485199d21df7695a8382",
