    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "004a06493dba4107aa7561f88601966c",
      "x": 29165.723890997073,
      "y": 3952.4277548911723,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.618000000000212,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Want to apply this to a specific good or sector, or keep it abstract for now?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "6b2ca75bb80b4ccaaee52386fa1a7556",
      "x": 41791.88530243194,
      "y": 16302.843253587373,
      "width": 316.57865149090503,
      "height": 214.31632432877996,
      "z_value": -9.529000000000261,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "What did the deterministic training period look like in practice \u2014 what were you actually doing during it, on what cadence, and how did you know it was working versus when you were just performing the steps? And the harder one: how do you detect now when your reflex pattern itself needs revision, given that the very thing that would've flagged it (the explicit chain) has been absorbed into the thing being audited? That's the recursion problem reflexes have, and the people who solve it are rare."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "87d715e0592442268764d1f218f2606f",
      "x": 29284.068380470937,
      "y": 5831.645855203813,
      "width": 308.9771097037592,
      "height": 146.7291080231762,
      "z_value": -9.612000000000215,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The layered approach told you where bottlenecks live. The modular approach tells you what each node actually is as a functional unit \u2014 its inputs, its conversion logic, its outputs, its tolerances. You get a per-node \"shape.\""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "69a389e922b74f258395b4d487b82a62",
      "x": 55576.43775368795,
      "y": 12898.009199818327,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 254.0,
      "z_value": -9.299000000000389,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "1. Closing the underlying FD is necessary but not sufficient.\n2. settimeout-based polling is necessary but not sufficient either \u2014 on Windows, listening sockets don't honour it reliably.\n3. The only guaranteed wakeup for a blocked accept() is to connect to it. Self-connect wakeup is the belt; polled timeout is the suspenders.\n4. Shutdown work that depends on a live interpreter belongs on aboutToQuit, not atexit. By the time atexit fires, Py_Finalize is already tearing things down around you."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "c52942aebdd449e4a40732309e0fe436",
      "x": 25583.123001722244,
      "y": -1608.0065275944166,
      "width": 319.2318687833322,
      "height": 237.62633011250546,
      "z_value": -9.6390000000002,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Historical population growth \u2014 measured against potential growth per context Key idea: compare actual trajectories to what was theoretically possible given each era's constraints (food, disease, tech, geography, social structure). The gap = the interesting part.\nPrimary goods and services \u2014 (awaiting your take)\nWhat angle here \u2014 the economic-sector sense (extraction/agriculture/raw materials), the Rawlsian \"primary goods\" sense (basic things any rational person would want), or something else?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "97eff474c4ea45ceb858d5cbf2c7c987",
      "x": 73646.5836912761,
      "y": 18655.173733271506,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 170.0,
      "z_value": -9.227000000000428,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "This is the same pattern GitNode Phase 3 (2026-04-16) landed on: neutralise dangerous QObject-level machinery synchronously before the deferred window, but leave scene-graph children (proxy, buttons, ports) intact so Qt's own removeItem can tear them down cleanly."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "517cfb3b6fcd4a60b7a722e30027d5e3",
      "x": 98394.23629392167,
      "y": 31289.446965985342,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 142.0,
      "z_value": -9.111000000000493,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "fault.txt showed the main thread in the normal Qt event loop \u2014 the crash was a queued positionChanged meta-call landing on a dead AudioNode wrapper."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Step, What, and Why",
      "uuid": "e557601b91f34dd5b6c9375c1a6e852f",
      "x": 99045.7714304912,
      "y": 32051.953113884847,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 408.0,
      "z_value": -9.107000000000495,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "1 Removed _demolition_workers manifest entry for _player Signal disconnection needs to happen inside _demolition_pre synchronously, not in the post-walk\n2 Added synchronous disconnect of durationChanged, positionChanged, mediaStatusChanged in _demolition_pre (each wrapped in try/except (RuntimeError, TypeError)) Severs the cross-thread edge before the player is stopped\n3 Replaced QTimer.singleShot(0, self._player.stop) with synchronous self._player.stop() No deferred window for queued meta-calls\n4 Added self._player.setAudioOutput(None) Severs the player\u2192audio C++ chain\n5 Added self._player.deleteLater() + self._audio.deleteLater() Schedules deterministic C++ teardown\n6 Added belt-and-braces shiboken6.isValid(self) guard at the top of _on_duration, _on_position, _on_media_status Receive-side net \u2014 a queued meta-call that got past the disconnect returns silently instead of crashing"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Files touched",
