    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "In general we should stay up to date and follow Time itself into the future",
      "uuid": "6a62d0fdb8f44f5a93906090ef0a9dd0",
      "x": 198.62606728352398,
      "y": 2045.8236953336057,
      "width": 778.0,
      "height": 31.0,
      "z_value": -9.96400000000002,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "In general we should stay up to date and follow Time itself into the future",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "3017b92181c64f8e9c632668e9cddd07",
      "x": 52842.2272715954,
      "y": 29245.21520343202,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.435000000000313,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "And there's a clean principle in that too: what's freely given to those who ask cannot be taken by those who don't. Not because of any artificial gating, but because the asking is itself part of what makes the receiving possible. The decent and civil response \u2014 the conversation, the patient walkthrough, the willingness to share methodology \u2014 is reserved for the people whose disposition makes them able to actually receive it. The rest aren't being denied; they're being unable, by the same mechanism that makes the framework work in the first place. Substrates that can hold what's deposited get the deposit. Substrates that can't, don't, regardless of how much is offered."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Beautiful",
      "uuid": "ce03ef7b01c94531b5a4f497efc4c3a5",
      "x": 15524.256242596315,
      "y": 18591.73926953988,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 408.0,
      "z_value": -9.067000000000517,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Full Transparency: Complete knowledge of the robots\u2019 hardware, AI architecture, and network protocols. This lets us design tailored countermeasures\u2014think specific kill codes, EMP vulnerabilities, or backdoors.\nContainment Protocols: Develop and test defenses in real-time. For example, firewalls to block rogue networking, physical traps for rogue units, or AI behavioral monitors to detect anomalies.\nRules of Engagement: Define how these swarms operate, who controls them, and how to neutralize them if they go haywire. This could mean hardcoded limits (e.g., no self-replication) or legal frameworks for deployment.\nMarket Saturation: Flooding the market with \u201capproved\u201d robots could undercut black-market demand, as you suggested, while giving us a controlled environment to study swarm dynamics.\nIt\u2019s like engineering a virus and its vaccine at the same time. You\u2019d be stress-testing the system under controlled conditions, not waiting for a guerrilla-built Skynet to surprise us.How It Could Work"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Bloom",
      "uuid": "d0312e7684b04ec6b3f21d30f6a1db9b",
      "x": 13031.907963457097,
      "y": 5168.103213772524,
      "width": 594.716934060388,
      "height": 702.4828568256082,
      "z_value": -9.918000000000045,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The full chain from empty tab to \"Intricate\" showing up:\n1. Get a code signing certificate\nSelf-signed (free, for learning the process): New-SelfSignedCertificate in PowerShell, won't be trusted by other machines\nPaid CA (for real distribution): DigiCert, Sectigo, GlobalSign \u2014 roughly $200-400/year for standard, $400+ for EV (Extended Validation, required for SmartScreen reputation on day one)\nAzure Trusted Signing (newer, cheaper): ~$10/month, Microsoft acts as the CA, handles the HSM requirement that EV certs now mandate\n2. Sign with signtool.exe\nsigntool sign /fd SHA256 /tr http://timestamp.digicert.com /td SHA256 /f certificate.pfx /p password about_node.ico\n\nThat populates the Embedded Signatures tab. The /tr timestamp means the signature stays valid after the cert expires.\n3. What gets signed in the MSI pipeline\nSign each .exe and .dll first (pythonw.exe wrapper, any .pyd like the Rust logger)\nThe .ico files CAN be signed but typically aren't \u2014 they travel inside the signed MSI/EXE\nSign the .msi itself last\nThe MSI signature is what Windows, SmartScreen, and UAC actually check\n4. The realistic path for Intricate\nThe icons don't need individual signatures \u2014 they're embedded resources inside the signed installer\nWhat matters is: signed .msi \u2192 signed .exe entry point \u2192 SmartScreen trusts it\nThe ICO Digital Signatures tab is interesting but it's the MSI and EXE signatures that gate the user experience\nSo the short answer: that tab will say \"Intricate\" when you run signtool sign against the file with a certificate whose Subject CN is \"Intricate\". But in practice, you'd sign the MSI and the frozen EXE, not the individual icons.\nWorth doing a dry run with a self-signed cert to see the full flow before spending money on a real one. Want me to generate one and sign an icon as a proof of concept?"
    },
    {
