    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Bright Tomorrow",
      "uuid": "5130e1af21f3441ea7c9c16f1441086c",
      "x": 51284.85499137229,
      "y": -3987.4479833091664,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 744.0,
      "z_value": -8.903000000000608,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Paragraph triage by length \u2014 _CALLOUT_MAX_CHARS = 90. Short paragraph \u2192 AboutNode pill, long \u2192 WarmNode panel. This is pure prose-weight introspection, not syntax. A meeting note like \"TODO: refactor the bridge\\n\\nThe bridge currently uses os.replace which...\" would split into a TODO sticker followed by a substance node \u2014 exactly the visual semantic the text already implies. Strongest candidate.\nis_structural_only \u2014 skip pure ---, ***, ===, decorator runs. Format-agnostic. Already a pure function in label_cleanup.py.\nprettify_label \u2014 ISO date \u2192 human, em-dash \u2192 colon, strip **/*/`/box-drawing/trailing colon. Already format-blind. Currently WarmNode body gets a hand-rolled lighter pass per the doc; there's a real question whether body should get the full pass or just the title slot if we add one.\nis_aboutnode_unsuitable \u2014 > or \" in a short paragraph routes to WarmNode instead of AboutNode (sticker chrome can't carry those glyphs cleanly). Pairs with #1.\nFormat-coupled bits (the red candidates \u2014 leave them where they are)\nHeading sectioning (r'^#{1,6}\\s+') \u2014 couples to # syntax.\nMarkdown table parsing (_transform_markdown_table) \u2014 couples to |---|.\nBold-leading title extraction (_extract_leading_bold) \u2014 fires on **bold**. Could opportunistically apply to raw text but most pastes won't carry the markers; mostly a no-op.\nASCII tree conversion \u2014 couples to box-drawing chars.\nA new candidate that isn't in MarkdownNode at all\nFirst-line-as-title inference. The prose-convention cousin of _extract_leading_bold. If a paragraph's first line is \u226490 chars, ends with : / ., and is followed by more content on subsequent lines, treat first line as title, rest as body. Risk: over-fits on legitimate prose where the first sentence is just short. Probably opt-in via threshold, or only fires when first line + colon + newline is unambiguous. Worth a discussion of its own \u2014 this is the place where \"introspection of the what\" gets riskiest because there's no syntactic tell, only a vibe."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Inner Peace",
      "uuid": "f2bb8d57abe343a2864cc9377bfb7639",
      "x": 50188.893224619926,
      "y": -4729.106637782519,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 254.0,
      "z_value": -8.906000000000606,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The three split functions have converged\nCushionsNode _export, WarmNode _split_oversized_paste, and MarkdownNode _split_into_nodes now all use the same machinery downstream \u2014 paragraph_chunks (or chunk_text for finer cascades), wander_origin, spiral_place, Connection. The \"organic cellular\" bit you remembered about CushionsNode reads as ancestral \u2014 by the time paragraph_chunks got extracted, it became the homogenising layer all three agreed to share. They now differ only on three axes:"
    },
