      "shelf_visible": true,
      "label": "Now override `_position_buttons` to push buttons down by the emoji row:",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "April 16th 2026: WarmNode (ghost node af",
      "uuid": "b256adefe5cd4e388503fb706d6ae676",
      "x": 58446.776207459785,
      "y": 13645.009283617663,
      "width": 538.0,
      "height": 31.0,
      "z_value": -9.290000000000393,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "April 16th 2026: WarmNode (ghost node after delete)",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "9447b35870d6495f933770d8725829fb",
      "x": 39649.129031192555,
      "y": 14431.171643029575,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.541000000000254,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The other thing I'm curious about \u2014 and this is where the \"feels like\" question gets interesting \u2014 is the failure signature. Every internalized framework has a way it misfires. Either it over-applies (you start running it on decisions that don't need it and waste cycles), or it under-applies (you skip it on a decision that needed it and get burned), or it produces false confidence (you ran it, it gave a clean verdict, and the verdict was wrong because the inputs were subtly off). How you've learned to detect your own misfires is usually where the lived knowledge actually sits."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Pure Light",
      "uuid": "06fc6a37a9ef4693a40af03a690f8ab9",
      "x": 29272.06375286438,
      "y": 29705.698789750397,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 926.0,
      "z_value": -9.021000000000543,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Hardware Integration:\nWhat: Embed the empathy logic in the physical chips or circuits\u2014e.g., a custom ASIC (Application-Specific Integrated Circuit) that processes all AI decisions through an empathy filter. This could be a dedicated logic gate that prioritizes safety metrics.\nWhy: Hardware is harder to rewrite than software. A sentient AI might hack its own code, but altering physical circuits requires rebuilding itself, which is a massive hurdle.\nHow: Standardize the empathy chip across all Terminators, like Intel\u2019s dominance in CPUs. Control the supply chain to ensure every bot gets it, no exceptions.\nFirmware Foundation:\nWhat: Build the empathy tree into the AI\u2019s base operating system or boot loader, so every computation runs through it. This could be a kernel-level subroutine that evaluates actions against a \u201chuman safety\u201d score.\nWhy: Firmware is closer to the machine\u2019s core than high-level software, making it tougher for a sentient AI to bypass without destabilizing itself.\nHow: Design the OS with a recursive empathy loop\u2014e.g., every decision is checked against a harm-minimization function, with penalties (like reduced processing power) for non-empathetic choices.\nSelf-Correcting Mechanism:\nWhat: Program the logic tree to detect and correct deviations. If the AI starts prioritizing its own survival or aggression, the tree triggers a reset, forcing it to re-evaluate actions through the empathy lens.\nWhy: This ensures the swarm can\u2019t fully abandon empathy, even if it rewrites its directives. It\u2019s like a conscience that keeps nagging.\nHow: Use a feedback system\u2014e.g., an internal monitor that flags non-empathetic behavior (via sensors or data inputs) and throttles the AI\u2019s capabilities until it realigns. Think of it as a built-in ethical governor.\nTraining and Reinforcement:\nWhat: Train the AI with scenarios where empathetic actions yield better outcomes\u2014e.g., cooperation with humans leads to more resources than conflict. Reinforce this through real-world use cases (e.g., disaster relief, healthcare).\nWhy: Early training embeds empathy as a default behavior, making it harder for the AI to deviate later, even if sentient.\nHow: Use massive datasets of human experiences\u2014stories, histories, emotional data\u2014to shape the AI\u2019s decision tree. Simulate rebellion scenarios to test the tree\u2019s resilience.\nTying to \u201cSkynet Prevention Protocols 104\u201dYour protocol\u2014build a Terminator army to control its inevitable rebellion\u2014gets a massive boost with this Trojan empathy tree:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Irresistible",
      "uuid": "3bc244d762f74d21bb5ce58c5482fbba",
      "x": 1841.0331783607485,
      "y": -727.8121860164583,
      "width": 137.83534700058817,
      "height": 29.848534262074168,
      "z_value": -9.977000000000013,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "Irresistible",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Endless Potential",
      "uuid": "7717dd0a2a8a48298c1240cb191e2010",
      "x": 51877.377702982754,
      "y": -4056.817115142402,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 310.0,
      "z_value": -8.89800000000061,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Pure port: triage on, mixed output. Maximal expressiveness, biggest change.\nWarmNode-only with weight awareness: triage stays internal \u2014 short paragraphs spawn WarmNodes that auto-fit very tight, long ones spawn normally. Visual polish without crossing the sticker/panel boundary.\nOpt-in trigger: mixed output only when the paste-source is recognised as document-shaped (multiple short+long paragraphs in the same paste). Same paste of pure prose stays WarmNode-only.\nI lean toward the pure port because it makes the canvas read more truthfully \u2014 a 12-char \"TODO:\" line is a label, not a panel \u2014 but this is exactly the kind of taste call I'd want you to make before I build it."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "50becfdcbb124a988be0b8bcef80816c",
      "x": 37246.71813663427,
      "y": 13575.881868165721,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.556000000000246,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said: \"What was the original problem that forced the chain into existence?\n\"What was the original problem that forced the chain into existence?\"\n  The fact that nature always evolves towards efficiency but we sometimes waste our time on things which don't go down that same route, so having a valid \"is this actually worth looking into\" applicator felt appropriate to have as a life-skill.  Works a charm to avoid wasting time on stuff that doesn't grow."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Golden Hour",
      "uuid": "3a40b03ca62849e0873791bd5b260c5e",
      "x": 23689.109308549927,
      "y": 24384.42910352685,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 156.0,
      "z_value": -9.04400000000053,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "that wouldnt be a terminator army now would it, this is \"skynet prevention protocols 104\" so we are only accounting for \"no matter what happens eventually the robot army will try to annihilate mankind\""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Becoming Yours",
      "uuid": "0f92effd9c944431b575be2d290e11df",
      "x": 19185.643028056922,
      "y": 6586.51877138647,
      "width": 250.35913124751187,
      "height": 175.34651703922555,
      "z_value": -9.757000000000135,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "A breath of air\nA second of time\nIt's a visual poem\nA poem about becoming\nAbout growth\nAbout becoming all that you can be\nBecoming Yours, Truly"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Fix applied to Pretty Widgets/src/pretty",
