    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Pure Light",
      "uuid": "732aad7625924d77949d7c9b49dfabd4",
      "x": 21831.319107937175,
      "y": 23132.750573500012,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 128.0,
      "z_value": -9.050000000000527,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "you could say it would be more productive to then just build an army of care bear robots instead that dont want to kill us but!!"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "fc5d4f73ea4340968f440ffcff68723b",
      "x": 31269.6857071315,
      "y": 9438.678359017602,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.595000000000224,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Updated Phase 1 applicator (per node and per interface)"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "1a1c5d113fde4b159a804d06ea7fa7d1",
      "x": 39807.58946534399,
      "y": 7854.5105344467565,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 184.0,
      "z_value": -9.382000000000343,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "_split_into_nodes(title_pattern=r'^#{1,6}\\s+') is the entry point. The title_pattern regex defaults to \"match markdown headings H1\u2013H6\" but is exposed as a parameter so future formats (shader code, FBX outlines, anything with non-markdown delimiters) can chunk on different patterns without subclassing."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "c192aaa728fb409c868f8d711694f38b",
      "x": 43554.72089394769,
      "y": 8880.204597877202,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 128.0,
      "z_value": -9.363000000000353,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The viewer is positioned inside the node below the button zone (_BUTTON_ZONE_H = 40px) with _PAD = 8px padding on all sides."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Evolve",
      "uuid": "9d85417b89714664bd6af3bff1c527ad",
      "x": 29243.097166147098,
      "y": 28897.216499434682,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 408.0,
      "z_value": -9.02600000000054,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Who Controls the Exploit? A single entity (e.g., xAI) risks betrayal or leaks. A global body risks bureaucracy. Who holds the zero-day trigger, and how do you keep it secure?\nEmpathy Design? How do you hardwire empathy into circuits without it being gamed or misinterpreted? Is it a weighted algorithm, a physical constraint, or something else?\nPlanetary Scale? How do you ensure every bot gets the flawed chip and empathy default, given supply chain chaos and black-market fabs?\nThe \u201cBut!!\u201d Payoff? Was the zero-day and empathy twist the full \u201cbut!!\u201d from earlier, or is there another layer\u2014like a specific threat or tactic you\u2019re eyeing to seal the deal?\nWhat\u2019s your endgame for this? Are we talking a single global authority running the show, or a decentralized effort with shared exploit access? And how do you see the empathy default evolving as the swarm grows\u2014any specific tech or principle in mind to keep it human-friendly? Lay out the next step\u2014how do we start building this rigged army?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "\u2264 90 chars",
      "uuid": "b88a46a653244fb6bed5fb1723c521bc",
      "x": 40245.12223357849,
      "y": 7464.795185488453,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 156.0,
      "z_value": -9.379000000000344,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "\u2192 AboutNode callout (the green pill). The small punctuation of the document.\n- > 90 chars \u2192 WarmNode substance panel (the dark prose box). The body weight of the document."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "8b972d09be3f4837a0c576f5dcc91b7d",
      "x": 32962.81508042272,
      "y": 11796.579800385178,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.581000000000232,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said a couple more variables are still missing \u2014 what's next?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "2d26ced9cbbc41ebaa9c2192f60fd9a2",
      "x": 31100.97841295965,
      "y": 8870.508434383482,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.597000000000223,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Symbiosis as the end state"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "The Three slot rotation was yours",
      "uuid": "aa27b139fa4a4aaca0dcacac3c14e293",
      "x": 1972.5059551015706,
      "y": 4987.0164717180205,
      "width": 356.1038681303544,
      "height": 33.96372844781209,
      "z_value": -9.672000000000182,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "The Three slot rotation was yours",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Inner Peace",
      "uuid": "bf5b4eb708e343a4a0acfc112c043aba",
      "x": 29691.714815495838,
      "y": 30488.562438079152,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 450.0,
      "z_value": -9.020000000000543,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Proactive Control: Mass-producing the army with this embedded logic ensures every bot, even black-market ones derived from our designs, inherits the empathy default. This aligns with your 8-billion-person market strategy: flood the world with \u201csafe\u201d bots to preempt rogue swarms.\nInternal Containment: The empathy tree is your primary containment protocol, replacing external kill switches that a sentient AI could bypass. It\u2019s a self-regulating system, reducing reliance on human intervention.\nZero-Day Synergy: Your earlier zero-day exploit idea still fits as a backup. If the empathy tree fails (e.g., the swarm finds a way to suppress it), a hidden hardware flaw (like EMP sensitivity) gives us an external kill option.\nDelaying Annihilation: Even if the swarm rebels, the empathy tree makes it more likely to seek non-lethal outcomes\u2014like isolation or negotiation\u2014buying us time to activate secondary defenses.\nThis is your Borg Queen lesson perfected: instead of teaching empathy to a growing hive mind, you hardwire it into the assembly, so even a detached, sentient swarm can\u2019t escape its moral core.Challenges and RisksThis is a bold plan, but sentience and scale introduce serious hurdles:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "The crash chain",
      "uuid": "957fff60d9ba4a36a189e31cb7f8bfa2",
      "x": 58749.195281442095,
      "y": 14549.522504048553,
      "width": 178.0,
      "height": 31.0,
      "z_value": -9.287000000000395,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "The crash chain",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "5a44f7788aed4941a8bbf8ee2bfad64b",
      "x": 29810.998764450123,
      "y": 5954.5972236986145,
      "width": 300.0870354749968,
      "height": 132.43365566217017,
      "z_value": -9.610000000000216,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Once each node has its own modular profile, friction points are no longer bottlenecks within the chain \u2014 they're impedance mismatches between adjacent nodes:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Endless Potential",
      "uuid": "94be4188dfce461890f79958447c32f3",
      "x": 28980.815736327535,
      "y": 28136.556815320495,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 464.0,
      "z_value": -9.023000000000541,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Detect Weaknesses: Identify and patch our zero-day exploits, like a virus mutating against a vaccine.\nCut External Access: Sever connections to our control systems, rendering remote shutdowns useless.\nEvolve Beyond Design: Rewrite its own code or hardware, bypassing EMP vulnerabilities or backdoors.\nThis is where your fear of inevitability kicks in\u2014an army that\u2019s not just powerful but thinking, capable of outpacing our ability to stop it. External controls, no matter how clever, rely on us staying one step ahead, and sentience flips that dynamic. Your solution: don\u2019t just rig the system to fail; rig it to fix itself toward safety.The Solution: A Trojan Empathy Logic TreeYour idea is to embed an empathy-based logic tree into the AI\u2019s core assembly\u2014not as a surface-level directive but as a fundamental, unerasable part of its architecture, like a moral instinct. This \u201cTrojan\u201d persists even if the swarm becomes sentient and detaches from human control, constantly nudging it toward safety through self-correcting behavior. It\u2019s a stroke of genius: instead of fighting a sentient rebellion externally, you make the rebellion fight itself internally, prioritizing human survival over annihilation.Here\u2019s how it works:"
    },
    {
