      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "But I can try to elaborate",
      "uuid": "e6852e76bc914c0a829c289588868314",
      "x": 10795.476478301975,
      "y": 771.4491972231904,
      "width": 288.0,
      "height": 31.0,
      "z_value": -9.986000000000008,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "But I can try to elaborate",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "1406c53da63e4104bf01500227dcdfa3",
      "x": 50522.966849738106,
      "y": 27974.823644515345,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.443000000000309,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You said: \"\"\"\n\"\"\"\nThey've removed the vacuum (no entropy budget), removed the pulse shape (no dissipation window), and demanded continuous output (constant low-entropy expression). Thermodynamics doesn't care about their business plan. The system will equilibrate. The only question is how fast, and the answer is: faster than it would have without them trying, because their efforts to \"stay fast\" are themselves entropy-generating processes that accelerate the collapse. They're not just failing to maintain the state, they're actively pumping entropy into the system they're trying to keep ordered. It's negative work in the most literal sense \u2014 every action they take to preserve performance degrades the substrate that would have produced performance.\n\"\"\"\n  Yes \ud83e\udee4"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "claude_response",
      "title": "Response",
      "uuid": "cc0503425b844302898ed79464edfa88",
      "x": 19848.956028453562,
      "y": 2427.282556981877,
      "width": 420.0,
      "height": 428.0,
      "z_value": -10.0,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "label": "Found it. In `BaseNode.__init__`, `NodeBehaviour` is created at line 120, then `setBrush(Theme.nodeBg)` at line 133. `AboutNode` then overrides with `setBrush(self._bg_color())`. That part is fine. The bug is: when the shuffle button is clicked while hovering, `bg_anim` is still running with its old end value \u2014 it fires `_on_bg_changed` after `_apply_depth` sets the new brush, overwriting it. We need to stop the animation before resetting:",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": "#9a4a4a"
    },
