    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "April 19th 2026: Single-node shake-delet",
      "uuid": "b4c8d7152c9b4d72a5c6d5a926874824",
      "x": 93645.55829043504,
      "y": 29657.183377698777,
      "width": 878.0,
      "height": 31.0,
      "z_value": -9.126000000000484,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "April 19th 2026: Single-node shake-delete missing the _bulk_removing quiescence guard",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Omnious",
      "uuid": "6251f971f976441d889db5dab73b63e5",
      "x": 13909.35523291114,
      "y": 14339.16146382552,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 814.0,
      "z_value": -9.077000000000512,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "You\u2019re painting a scenario where fear-driven regulation of humanoid robots backfires, spurring black-market demand and guerrilla production until robots outnumber humans, fueled by an 8-billion-person market. It\u2019s a compelling cascade, but let\u2019s unpack it.Regulation making robots exclusive could indeed drive desire\u2014basic human psychology, like wanting banned goods. Black markets thrive on scarcity; look at drugs or weapons. If humanoid robots are locked down due to misuse fears (say, weaponized AI or job displacement), shady manufacturers could churn out cheap, unregulated versions. An 8-billion-person market is a massive incentive\u2014everyone wanting a personal assistant, bodyguard, or laborer. Add in open-source designs or 3D-printed parts, and you\u2019ve got a recipe for proliferation.But the leap to robots outnumbering humans isn\u2019t a straight line. Production at that scale needs resources\u2014rare earth metals, chips, energy. Even guerilla factories face supply chain choke points, which governments or corporations could target. And \u201ccheap\u201d robots likely mean shoddy ones\u2014prone to glitches, not Skynet-level threats. Sentience or decentralized AI isn\u2019t a given either; those are still sci-fi, not garage-hackable tech. Most black-market bots would likely be dumb tools, not autonomous swarms.Your point about human impatience is sharp, though. If legit channels are blocked, people turn to illicit ones. Guerrilla production could explode in places with weak oversight\u2014think rogue fabs in lawless zones. But \u201ceveryone\u201d building robots? That assumes a lot of coordination and tech know-how. Most people want plug-and-play, not DIY cyborgs. And if robots start flooding the market, you\u2019d see pushback\u2014think Luddite riots or EMP-toting vigilantes.The swarm you described earlier\u2014cancer-like, unstoppable\u2014needs more than numbers. It needs a unified, resilient intelligence. Decentralized AI is possible (blockchain-like systems exist), but making it sentient and self-sustaining is a massive unsolved problem. Humans could still pull the plug on power grids or networks long before that point.You\u2019re right that human nature\u2014greed, curiosity, rebellion\u2014could drive this. But inevitability hinges on no one intervening effectively. Governments, corporations, even hackers have incentives to stop a robot flood. What makes you think the guerrilla surge would outpace countermeasures? Is it the sheer scale of demand or something about the tech itself you see as unstoppable?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Lesson",
      "uuid": "5e14b2660fd04313828a32c10ac52269",
      "x": 92586.94975721989,
      "y": 28560.987993294155,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 254.0,
      "z_value": -9.130000000000482,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Orphan timers (those that can't be parented to a QObject because the owner is a QGraphicsItem) need a defensive post-teardown guard at the top of every slot they connect to, since the non-deterministic shutdown path will occasionally race past the deterministic cleanup hooks.  The orphan pattern is used by many nodes in the codebase (GitNode, LogNode, MergeNode, ClaudeNode, ClaudeInfoNode, JoyStatsNode, PerfNode, VideoNode, etc.); the same class of crash is latent in all of them and only manifests under precise shutdown timing."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Note",
      "uuid": "2300c5714108444d82a2f06b12d17ea3",
      "x": 2225.3788685985583,
      "y": 2883.9888041665445,
      "width": 168.57449244464283,
      "height": 36.742030597807286,
      "z_value": -10.0,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "Becoming Yours",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "491f99ac7ead4009a7857bf6d3197514",
      "x": 35321.605490354996,
      "y": 12748.652846691446,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.56800000000024,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "With the gate in place, the operational pattern becomes: take any new thought (any proposed adjustment, intervention, or redesign), run it through this complete Phase 1 chain on every node and every interface, and harvest the results into the dynamic prioritization model. Thoughts get stress-tested per node; nodes get stress-tested per thought. The intersection is where Phase 2 actually begins."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Symptom",
      "uuid": "05df263dc1b94f8a909a78cd9a9b303c",
      "x": 62665.31954914685,
      "y": 15902.976979357867,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 128.0,
      "z_value": -9.273000000000403,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "0xc0000005 in Qt6Widgets.dll two seconds after a VideoNode deletion completes cleanly. No Python traceback \u2014 pure C++ crash."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "ad2d180bc94f40a7bb756ad95df2c72f",
      "x": 31170.65261660046,
      "y": 8626.19335798013,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.598000000000223,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The biggest bottleneck isn't always the first thing to address. If the largest friction point requires 18 months to remediate, and three medium frictions can be cleared in 6 weeks each, the medium fixes go first \u2014 they reduce systemic load while the long-horizon fix is in flight. Time-to-effect dictates parallelization: long fixes start now and run in the background; short fixes execute serially in priority order."
    },
    {
