    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Golden Hour",
      "uuid": "728d51dcc3564a21acda308a3cd4dcdf",
      "x": 39138.9170414217,
      "y": 38119.57291507507,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 534.0,
      "z_value": -8.99000000000056,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Old Approach: If the CPU detects no immediate empathy violations (e.g., no harmful actions planned), it stops correcting and assumes all is well. This risks missing latent errors\u2014like a robot prioritizing its own efficiency over human well-being in subtle ways\u2014that could escalate in a sentient swarm.\nNew Approach: The CPU keeps error-correcting until it confirms all possible errors within its scope (e.g., current tasks, future plans, network interactions) are resolved. For example, it might adjust a decision that\u2019s technically \u201csafe\u201d but suboptimal for human welfare, like choosing to save more lives in a disaster scenario. Only when all empathy-related issues are solved does it pause correction, while remaining ready to restart if new issues arise.\nTertiary Operation Default: As you specified, during correction, the robot keeps \u201ceverything operational on all tertiary unrelated fields\u201d (e.g., navigation, sensors, non-lethal tasks), ensuring it stays functional and useful, avoiding downtime that could alert a sentient AI or disrupt market adoption.\nThis is like training a pet in the womb to not just avoid biting but to actively seek ways to protect its owner, only resting when every threat in its environment is addressed.Implementing the Empathy Logic Tree with Dynamic Error-CorrectionTo embed this in the Terminator army\u2019s CPU at the circuit level\u2014your \u201csimple genetics\u201d approach\u2014here\u2019s how we\u2019d design it:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "File, Issue, and Fix",
      "uuid": "56e37279d29641b1bbd69987a693d9ac",
      "x": 91231.87732698528,
      "y": 26677.815482109934,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 436.0,
      "z_value": -9.141000000000476,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "BloomNode.py proxy.setWidget(None) without scene.removeItem(proxy) Added scene.removeItem() before detach\nClaudeNode.py Same \u2014 two proxies (_input_proxy, _body_proxy) Added scene.removeItem() for both\nMergeNode.py Same \u2014 _list_proxy Added scene.removeItem()\nPaletteNode.py Same \u2014 _title_proxy, _palette_proxy Added scene.removeItem() for both\nSequenceNode.py Same \u2014 _slider_proxy Added scene.removeItem()\nTextNode.py Same \u2014 _html_proxy Added scene.removeItem()\nTreeNode.py Same \u2014 _toolbar_proxy Added scene.removeItem()\nValueNode.py Same \u2014 _slider_proxy Added scene.removeItem()\nScene.py (\u00d72 paths) _glide_timer.stop() without .disconnect() Added timeout.disconnect(_glide_tick)\nmain_window.py _tooltip_timer = QTimer() without parent Changed to QTimer(self) + disconnect on cancel"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "1532f5cb43874b2ca3bfe3854184b3a7",
      "x": 45228.3249375079,
      "y": 19600.098096411693,
      "width": 316.69717578760174,
      "height": 258.8336721228152,
      "z_value": -9.493000000000281,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "So the macro example doesn't just illustrate the principle; it proves it twice, in two different substrates (silicon and biology), with two different training mediums (token interaction and lived decision-making), producing the same emergent property (compressed precision manifesting as speed), and producing the same dark-mirror failure in any imitator who tries to skip the saturation phase. That's not a coincidence \u2014 it's evidence the principle is substrate-independent, which means it's probably a real law of how chained systems achieve high-performance precision states, not a quirk of any particular medium."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "2. StickerNode override",
      "uuid": "0e0e84a04dd8432d81aa984cfe7f5b8b",
      "x": 86637.60151997262,
      "y": 24337.505275235802,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 226.0,
      "z_value": -9.160000000000466,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "(nodes/StickerNode.py).\n- _quiet_for_shake() synchronously calls _disconnect_viewport_tracking() \u2014 severs both scrollbar signals before the deferred window opens.\n- _on_viewport_changed() gains three guards: shiboken6.isValid(self), scene._bulk_removing > 0 early-return, and self._removal_done early-return. Any scrollbar tick that slips through the disconnect still can't mutate a dying node."
    },
