    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Unfold",
      "uuid": "bda5f6142a5f41438bcf3d165ef66b68",
      "x": 39713.02076863787,
      "y": 40915.381879797336,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 478.0,
      "z_value": -8.985000000000563,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "What It Means: The empathy logic tree scans the robot\u2019s scope\u2014current tasks, future plans, or swarm interactions\u2014for any deviation from human safety, like aggressive actions or subtle inefficiencies that could indirectly harm humans (e.g., prioritizing robot survival over human welfare). It then allocates resources to resolve these issues, only pausing when all errors are fixed. For example, a Terminator in a disaster zone might reroute its efforts to save trapped humans rather than secure its own power source, even if the latter is \u201csafe.\u201d\nWhy It\u2019s Proactive: By continuing until all errors are solved, the mechanism forces the AI to anticipate and address potential issues, not just react to obvious ones. This is like a pet not just avoiding danger but actively seeking ways to protect its owner, using its instincts to spot threats early.\nTertiary Operation Default: During correction, systems unrelated to the error (e.g., mobility, sensors) stay fully functional, ensuring the robot remains useful and doesn\u2019t signal to a sentient AI that it\u2019s being constrained. This maintains market appeal and prevents rebellion triggers.\nImplementing the Proactive Empathy Logic TreeTo embed this in the Terminator army\u2019s CPU at the circuit level\u2014your \u201csimple genetics\u201d approach\u2014here\u2019s how we\u2019d design it in robotics terms:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Root cause",
      "uuid": "84997a6e946144128e407ef0c44f0806",
      "x": 60853.2664788378,
      "y": 14777.569439918028,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 184.0,
      "z_value": -9.2790000000004,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "PrettyEdit.teardown() called proxy.setWidget(None) to sever C++ ownership of the QTextEdit, but left the QGraphicsProxyWidget itself in the scene graph as a child of the parent node. When Qt's paint loop reached the zombie proxy, it dereferenced the severed widget pointer \u2192 access violation."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
