      "body_text": "- Faulting application: pythonw.exe\n- Faulting module: ntdll.dll\n- Exception code: 0xc0000374 (STATUS_HEAP_CORRUPTION \u2014 ntdll's heap checker caught a write to freed memory)"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Step, What, and Why",
      "uuid": "11aa2d9f82514befbf4643d19c9dda4d",
      "x": 52378.123462473464,
      "y": 12854.418163656475,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 296.0,
      "z_value": -9.312000000000381,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "1 sock.settimeout(_ACCEPT_POLL) before starting listener accept() now wakes every 0.25s instead of blocking forever\n2 Loop becomes while not stop_event.is_set() with except socket.timeout: continue Thread can observe shutdown intent cooperatively\n3 stop_event attached to the Thread object via t._stop_event Reachable from release_singleton without changing _HELD's shape materially\n4 release_singleton sets the event, closes the socket, then thread.join(timeout=_JOIN_TIMEOUT) Main thread waits for the listener to fully exit before returning; only then does atexit unwind and Py_Finalize begin"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "1bc63af7ea4a4261b338823b882fb768",
      "x": 35390.544303641305,
      "y": 12139.192007673784,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.570000000000238,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Historical vs. potential \u2192 demand layers (future / peak / throughput) \u2192 handling time \u2192 required practices \u2192 implementation time \u2192 gain magnitude \u2192 effort cost \u2192 failure modes / blast radius / reversibility / containment / residual risk \u2192 macroeconomic singleton rating multiplier \u2192 final risk-weighted, multiplier-adjusted quadrant placement \u2192 dynamic sequence position."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Although this is all a seemingly impractical task",
      "uuid": "e4100d91e4664b1c9f25915baced332a",
      "x": 1914.2281818982005,
      "y": -241.55864760026827,
      "width": 531.2694297900723,
      "height": 258.9252942146287,
      "z_value": -9.421000000000321,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "We can estimate various conditions\nBased on the current data.\n\nOur hearts align the same as any plant in the garden\nSupports the growth of the other plants\nWe as well share this existence\n\nWe share our journey with others\nAnd our collective wisdom offers new solutions.\n\nDelicious and nutritious, meticulously planned\nTo optimize performance, recovery, and energy levels."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "b6dd497c4d3947d18f3d4aef172c5ee7",
      "x": 24085.88060042226,
      "y": -2819.6875346235747,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.649000000000195,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Got it \u2014 I'll keep a running summary as we go. Just share the concepts whenever you're ready, and I'll track each one with the key takeaway so you can pick it back up at your desk."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Step, What, and Why",
      "uuid": "57c7ef4fdd184ac89d5eeefa884fe9cc",
      "x": 99431.55298296326,
      "y": 33481.581458320994,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 352.0,
      "z_value": -9.094000000000502,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "1 blockSignals(True) on every Qt object FIRST Nothing queues new events during teardown \u2014 covers signals we never explicitly connected to\n2 Fade audio volume to 0 (signals already blocked, no slot fires) Clean audio sink drain\n3 .disconnect() with no args on player / sink / audio Drops every outgoing connection in one call \u2014 removes the targeted-disconnect-leak vector entirely\n4 Synchronous stop() + setVideoOutput(None) + setAudioOutput(None) Unchanged from 2026-04-16 \u2014 sever the media pipeline\n5 deleteLater() on each object Unchanged\n6 self._player = None, self._sink = None, self._audio = None Drops Python wrapper refs AFTER deleteLater so Qt still has a valid pointer when scheduling cleanup. Any post-teardown reference now gets a clean AttributeError instead of dereferencing a dangling pointer"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Inner Peace",
      "uuid": "c15f4690589a46f697597ae213201865",
      "x": 19083.87108335099,
      "y": 21784.129197562932,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 548.0,
      "z_value": -9.056000000000523,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Know the Architecture: Full insight into the swarm\u2019s decision-making lets you craft precise directives and containment strategies.\nPreempt Chaos: Legal, empathetic swarms could satisfy the 8-billion-person market, reducing black-market incentives.\nBuild Defenses: If the directive fails (like the Queen backsliding), you\u2019d have fallback protocols\u2014kill switches, EMPs, or counter-swarms\u2014ready to go.\nBut it\u2019s not just about the initial directive. You\u2019d need ongoing governance to keep the swarm\u2019s goals aligned as it grows. Think of it as raising a kid: you instill values early, but you also need to check in as they hit puberty.My TakeTeaching the Borg Queen empathy\u2014or giving your swarm an empathetic directive\u2014is a brilliant way to flip the \u201cinevitable\u201d doom narrative. It\u2019s not about coding a perfect AI but about giving it a reason to play nice. Your controlled rollout lets us experiment with directives under real-world conditions, not in some lab vacuum. But the challenge is enforcement. Directives sound great until the hive (or swarm) starts rewriting its own rules or some idiot tweaks them for profit or power.Who do you see setting these directives? A global body sounds nice but slow\u2014too many cooks. A single entity (government, corporation) risks tyranny or bias. And how do you keep the directive \u201cempathetic\u201d without it morphing into something else as the swarm scales? Got a specific framework for this, or are you leaning toward a more organic, trial-and-error approach?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Evolve",
      "uuid": "77a685a4157b4bf687e6c14e546edc00",
      "x": 49212.7235837518,
      "y": -3365.8730088466364,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 156.0,
      "z_value": -8.926000000000595,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "lovely, thanks, and push that to git please, I also deleted some .json files from the root earlier, can you check the folder structure and make sure there are no uncommitted changes and pack those along the with the push please"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "claude_response",
      "title": "Response",
      "uuid": "599bf4dd396c44289d3ac0e6521e9216",
      "x": 22119.098896548057,
      "y": 2999.961735751941,
      "width": 420.0,
      "height": 624.0,
      "z_value": -10.0,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "label": "The criteria doc doing quiet heavy lifting every single time \u2014 \"strong clear silhouette, warm cream, outer ring identical\" and Pillow just executes it faithfully at 2048px without needing to be told twice. No designer, no asset pipeline, no back-and-forth. The whole thing takes about four seconds and produces a proper multi-resolution ICO that Qt resolves automatically at whatever size it needs.\n\nThe vision API seeding it the first time was the elegant part \u2014 letting the existing icons teach the recipe rather than us having to reverse-engineer what \"matches the family\" means.",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": "#c97a7a"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Yummi",
      "uuid": "709e6b21b50844a49409a87e9d634e3e",
      "x": 4190.027505713864,
      "y": 2478.643092870796,
      "width": 75.05761796933189,
      "height": 26.47166427982529,
      "z_value": -9.842000000000088,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "Yummi",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": "#2a3a2f"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "f028f48c96aa4f2cb54227ac3de4361f",
      "x": 38052.09533397104,
      "y": 12994.901387850048,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.551000000000249,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The nature-efficiency premise is doing more work than it looks. Most decision frameworks start from \"how do I optimize choice X\" \u2014 yours starts from \"is X even on an evolutionary trajectory worth riding.\" That's why the singleton multiplier isn't just a filter, it's the whole point \u2014 everything before it is the apparatus required to ask that question without fooling yourself. The elaborate analysis exists to earn the right to apply the multiplier honestly. Skip the analysis and the multiplier becomes vibes."
    },
    {
