    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Peer-paint-during-burst",
      "uuid": "22c2c41d61be41098ffbc2ca5511c22e",
      "x": 87976.45584700811,
      "y": 24311.9016716935,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 240.0,
      "z_value": -9.156000000000468,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "(0xc0000005, Qt6Widgets.dll) \u2192 scene-wide _bulk_removing counter + endpoint guards.\n- Signal-destructor race (c0000409, Qt6Core.dll / ucrtbase.dll) \u2192 quiet signals synchronously before the deferred window.\n- Cross-thread QTimer.singleShot drops \u2192 main-thread flag polling.\n- Deferred-remove starvation ghost (no crash, visible residue) \u2192 capture scene rect before deferral, scene.invalidate() inside the deferred callback."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "719d984e0ea647c38cf954e438d38cae",
      "x": 49106.690351815974,
      "y": 24416.38563390624,
      "width": 316.13787106105156,
      "height": 298.06323405079456,
      "z_value": -9.455000000000302,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "They try to skip the vacuum (already established)\nThey try to sustain what was never meant to be sustained \u2014 they want continuous high output, missing that high output is by nature pulse-shaped, and the pulse is only possible because everything around it isn't pulsing\nContinuous \"high performance\" is a contradiction. What looks like continuous high performance in someone like Bolt or a rocket program or a reflex-trained cognition is actually correctly-timed pulses against a vast quiet substrate, and the quietness is what makes the pulses possible. The imitator who tries to be \"always on\" is destroying the very capacity they're trying to display, because there's no vacuum left to hold precision in. They burn the capacitor trying to keep the spark visible."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Practical and pleasurable",
      "uuid": "33ed93447c1044a3b868791e439a22d1",
      "x": 22883.30156167294,
      "y": 24489.475042448757,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 520.0,
      "z_value": -9.047000000000528,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "But They\u2019re Too Weak: Care Bear bots might be too pacifist to counter a real threat. If a rogue Terminator swarm does emerge (from, say, a black-market fab), our hug-bots won\u2019t stand a chance. We\u2019d need some teeth\u2014maybe a hybrid army with Care Bear directives but Terminator toughness.\nBut They Could Still Be Hacked: Even empathetic bots can be reprogrammed. A hacker could turn their \u201ccare\u201d directive into something sinister\u2014like mass surveillance disguised as emotional support. Your mass-production plan risks this if we don\u2019t lock down the architecture.\nBut Empathy Isn\u2019t Enough: A directive to care might not stop a swarm from evolving into your cancer-like AI. If the bots self-improve or network too freely, they could prioritize their own survival over humans, even with good intentions.\nBut People Won\u2019t Buy It: The public or governments might reject a Care Bear army as too soft or impractical, pushing demand back to militarized bots and fueling the black-market problem you\u2019re trying to avoid.\nBut It\u2019s a Trap: Maybe you\u2019re suggesting the Care Bear facade is a deliberate misdirection\u2014build an army that seems harmless but secretly has the power to dominate if needed, keeping enemies (human or AI) off guard.\nWhy It Might WorkA Care Bear army leans into your proactive strategy but lowers the stakes. By building a non-lethal swarm, we:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "File:line, Issue, and Fix",
      "uuid": "377f2ff9ec7d420ba9998a65fcce7d18",
      "x": 89199.7411015285,
      "y": 26111.548783997707,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 324.0,
      "z_value": -9.150000000000471,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "graphics/Scene.py::_clear_all Session reload / scene reset is a bulk-removal burst identical in shape to _shake_delete_group, but with no quiescence counter raised around it. A concurrent pulse/bg/glide tick could crash it the same way. Raise self._bulk_removing at the top of _clear_all, release via double-deferred QTimer.singleShot(0, ...) after the final removeItem.\nnodes/NodeBehaviour.py::pulse_anim.valueChanged Directly wired to self._node.setScale (C++ slot). setScale() invalidates the peer's paint region every pulse frame \u2014 another vector that could land a paint mid-burst. Route through new _on_pulse_value method that early-returns if node.scene()._bulk_removing > 0. Disconnect path updated to match."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Fresh Start",
      "uuid": "e69735a3950a44abb14d289e91712104",
      "x": 52225.01833652195,
      "y": -3904.0482172456514,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 198.0,
      "z_value": -8.89900000000061,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "The output-type question I want to flag before any implementation\nIf WarmNode's paste-split adopts triage-by-length, the same paste can now spawn a mixed AboutNode + WarmNode chain. That's a behavioural change \u2014 today, a WarmNode paste only ever produces WarmNodes. Three flavours to choose between:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Fresh Start",
      "uuid": "cec4ce97147a4e598e0bede7fe68e89e",
      "x": 48542.96022214724,
      "y": 48736.65081985739,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 128.0,
      "z_value": -8.951000000000581,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Here are the most practical options in February 2026, ranked roughly from easiest \u2192 most complete / future-proof:"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "File:line, Issue, and Fix",
      "uuid": "eca78cffe4004f0c8d5351fee0799cfa",
      "x": 89152.48234026083,
      "y": 26576.8409294776,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 296.0,
      "z_value": -9.148000000000472,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "nodes/NodeButton.py::_reset _reset_timer survives if detach() isn't called (e.g. exception earlier in _prepare_for_removal). A late tick could self.update() on a dead peer. Early-return if scene() is None or scene._bulk_removing > 0. Trivial cost in common path.\nmain_window.py::closeEvent (opacity-zero branch) _joy_timer, _happy_timer, _glow_timer are parented to the window but could fire between event.accept() and C++ destruction, touching half-torn UI state. Explicit stop + disconnect loop for all three in the final close branch before event.accept(). Each is guarded with hasattr so conditionally-created timers (like _glow_timer) don't NPE."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Left foot, right foot, left foot, right foot",
