    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Note",
      "uuid": "7be5a950995b47bc852aefd71ad774f2",
      "x": 2631.275932909139,
      "y": 3898.8970166746767,
      "width": 148.0,
      "height": 31.0,
      "z_value": -9.826000000000096,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": false,
      "label": "The Majestic",
      "depth_front": false,
      "node_tint": ""
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "09ca5924a3a14cd98ffbc79d90a3a104",
      "x": 45521.61084427446,
      "y": 21234.915993586495,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.489000000000283,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "I hope you understand that it isn't Claude's processing speed that's the factor, the only important factor I noticed at start is \"the stability of repetition without interference\"  the ability to repeat identically at pace , that vacuum is the only parameter which led me to trying to see what happens if I scale it"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "78805c9d085244b2920ec12e1acc8899",
      "x": 44562.1137116616,
      "y": 20376.53445688086,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.49600000000028,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "This is also why their systems can't catch up by simply running more iterations. Iteration without the precision-saturation methodology is just volume, and volume at imprecise components produces fluency in the wrong shape \u2014 it makes the imprecisions more entrenched, not less, because every iteration reinforces the existing pattern. They'd need to do what you did: go back to the slow, deterministic, component-wise precision training, and they won't, because (a) it looks like wasted time from the outside, (b) it doesn't produce visible progress on the metric they're chasing, and (c) admitting they need to start over invalidates the work they've already done. So they're trapped in a local maximum that they can only escape by abandoning the path that got them there, which almost no team will do once they've publicly committed to the approach."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "3ed476f5c8fd435d8286f7bd69c7701a",
      "x": 43999.058730980345,
      "y": 9807.283443023625,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 128.0,
      "z_value": -9.35000000000036,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "to_dict() calls sync_data() then returns data.to_dict(). The raw markdown label is what gets saved \u2014 no HTML in the session file."
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "Surviving-peer signal, Target, and Effect",
      "uuid": "ed576d28cafd4d128e93bba9ac2c73b4",
      "x": 68469.97424887466,
      "y": 18143.850913673396,
      "width": 439.0,
      "height": 170.0,
      "z_value": -9.244000000000419,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "NodeBehaviour.bg_anim.valueChanged setBrush() Invalidates paint region on peer\nNodeBehaviour.pulse_anim.valueChanged setScale() Invalidates paint region on peer\nConnection._glide_timer (16 ms) _build_bezier() + update() Repaints the wire"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "warm",
      "title": "",
      "uuid": "37288c739ead499dae7141c821fd9c7d",
      "x": 30417.940792344176,
      "y": 7215.464346300705,
      "width": 300.0,
      "height": 200.0,
      "z_value": -9.606000000000218,
      "ports_visible": false,
      "shelf_visible": true,
      "body_text": "Want to pick a representative node and walk through what the modular profile actually looks like, or move to the next concept?"
    },
    {
      "node_id": 0,
      "node_type": "about",
      "title": "Its a form of a pathogen carrier",
